Spending time in the sun can boost vitamin D levels, reducing the risk of breast and colorectal cancers.
Studies suggest taking 2,000 IU of vitamin D3 daily and getting sun exposure.
Vitamin D supplements are crucial, especially for those with low levels.
The sun's rays help the body produce vitamin D, essential for strong bones and cell growth regulation.
Canadians are advised to take 1,000 IU of vitamin D daily, with higher-risk individuals urged to do so year-round.
Sun exposure may lower breast cancer risk, but caution is advised due to skin cancer risks.
